import{o as e,c as r,e as o}from"./app.060d6601.js";const t='{"title":"Graphic file formats for web apps","description":"","frontmatter":{},"headers":[{"level":2,"title":"Exporting graphic assets","slug":"exporting-graphic-assets"},{"level":2,"title":"Raster graphic formats","slug":"raster-graphic-formats"},{"level":2,"title":"Vector format (SVG)","slug":"vector-format-svg"},{"level":2,"title":"Conclusion","slug":"conclusion"}],"relativePath":"graphics/vector-pixel/file-formats.md","lastUpdated":1630869125837}',a={},i=o('<h1 id="graphic-file-formats-for-web-apps"><a class="header-anchor" href="#graphic-file-formats-for-web-apps" aria-hidden="true">#</a> Graphic file formats for web apps</h1><p>You should know from your previous study about vector and pixel graphics and what distinguishes them. Then you also know, that there is a lot of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image_file_formats" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">different type file formats</a>, like JPG, TIFF, PSD, PDF, SVG, EPS, RAW and so on. But not all the formats are suitable for web developement.</p><p><strong>Here we will focus on the file formats, you can use in web developement ie what work in browsers.</strong></p><div class="tip custom-block"><p class="custom-block-title">Quick reminder</p><ul><li><strong>Raster <em>(aka Pixel or Bitmap)</em> graphics</strong> is made of pixels - tiny squares that have a certain color (and sometimes transparency). Like digital photos from your phone, for example. It is hard to enlarge pixel images, because we just do not have the data.</li><li><strong>Vector graphics</strong> is drawn with mathematic point coordinates, curves and equations, which can be recalculated each time. Thats&#39;s why vector graphics can be easily resized or even manipulated in real time.</li></ul><p><a href="https://vector-conversions.com/vectorizing/raster_vs_vector.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Read this</a> if you need more information.</p></div><div class="warning custom-block"><p class="custom-block-title">NOTE: canvas</p><p>Should we mention <code>&lt;canvas&gt;</code> here as an option to show and manipulate raster images on browser?</p></div><div class="warning custom-block"><p class="custom-block-title">NOTE: video</p><p>Where are we talking about <code>&lt;video&gt;</code>?</p></div><h2 id="exporting-graphic-assets"><a class="header-anchor" href="#exporting-graphic-assets" aria-hidden="true">#</a> Exporting graphic assets</h2><ul><li>From <a href="https://helpx.adobe.com/photoshop/using/export-artboards-layers.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Photoshop</a></li><li>From <a href="https://vectortwist.com/asset-export-illustrator/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Illustrator</a></li><li>From <a href="https://help.figma.com/hc/en-us/articles/360040028114-Guide-to-exports-in-Figma" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Figma</a></li><li>From After Effects <ul><li>As <a href="https://www.schoolofmotion.com/blog/gif-in-after-effects" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">animated GIF</a></li><li>Using <a href="https://lottiefiles.com/plugins/after-effects" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Lottie</a></li></ul></li><li>etc</li></ul><h2 id="raster-graphic-formats"><a class="header-anchor" href="#raster-graphic-formats" aria-hidden="true">#</a> Raster graphic formats</h2><ul><li><strong><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JPEG" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">JPG</a></strong></li><li><strong><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portable_Network_Graphics" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">PNG</a></strong><ul><li>Supports transparency <ul><li><a href="https://www.adobe.com/photoshop/online/transparent-background.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Adobe online tool</a></li><li><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P7aNejNEiPE" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">With Photoshop</a></li><li><a href="https://www.remove.bg/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Remove BG</a></li></ul></li><li>Animated PNGs (<strong>APNG</strong>) <ul><li>Rendering from After Effects</li><li><a href="https://ezgif.com/apng-maker" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">EzGif APNG converter</a></li></ul></li><li>Optimizing PNG <ul><li><a href="https://tinypng.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">TinyPNG</a></li></ul></li></ul></li><li><strong><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GIF" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GIF</a></strong> - mostly for animations <ul><li><a href="https://www.schoolofmotion.com/blog/gif-in-after-effects" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Animated GIFs</a></li></ul></li><li><strong><a href="https://developers.google.com/speed/webp" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">WebP</a></strong><ul><li>Supports animation</li><li>Supports transparency</li><li><a href="https://insanelab.com/blog/web-development/webp-web-design-vs-jpeg-gif-png/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Better quality/size ratio</a> than JPG or PNG</li><li>Helper tools and utilities - although there is pretty good browser support, WebP is not very widely supported by the mainstream design programs. That&#39;s why we need some extra tools or utilities to generate the WebP files. <ul><li><a href="https://developers.google.com/speed/webp/docs/precompiled" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Google converters</a></li><li><a href="https://developers.google.com/speed/webp/docs/webpshop" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Photoshop plugin</a></li><li><a href="https://cloudconvert.com/webp-converter" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">CloudConvert</a></li><li><a href="https://ezgif.com/webp-maker" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">EzGif WebP converter</a></li></ul></li></ul></li><li>When to choose each format <ul><li>ðŸ“Œ<a href="https://wpmudev.com/blog/best-image-formats-png-vs-jpg-svg-gif-webp/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">JPG vs PNG vs GIF vs WebP</a></li></ul></li></ul><p>âš  <em><mark>AVIF, JPEG XL, JPEG XR</mark> etc formats should be considered to cover later, when/if wider browser support becomes available</em></p><h2 id="vector-format-svg"><a class="header-anchor" href="#vector-format-svg" aria-hidden="true">#</a> Vector format (SVG)</h2><p>There are a bunch of different raster formats for web, but only one vector - the SVG</p><ul><li>ðŸ“Œ<a href="https://css-tricks.com/lodge/svg/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">All you have to know about SVG</a> (and probably more)</li></ul><div class="tip custom-block"><p class="custom-block-title">NOTE</p><p>There is only one link, so you may think that there isn&#39;t much to talk about. But wait, just click and see!</p></div><h2 id="conclusion"><a class="header-anchor" href="#conclusion" aria-hidden="true">#</a> Conclusion</h2><p>As you can read from <a href="https://dev.to/jsco/understanding-image-formats-on-the-web-4op8" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">this Dev.to article</a>, these are the basic rules, which format to choose:</p><ul><li>Use <strong>SVG for logos/icons/illustrations</strong> etc or anything you want to <strong>animate</strong></li><li>Use <strong>WEBP for everything else</strong> with either JPG or PNG as a fallback</li><li>Use <strong>JPEG</strong> for Photos (as a <strong>fallback for webp</strong>)</li><li>Use <strong>PNG</strong> for logos/illustrations etc <strong>when no SVG</strong> is available (as a <strong>fallback for webp</strong>)</li></ul>',18);a.render=function(o,t,a,l,s,n){return e(),r("div",null,[i])};export default a;export{t as __pageData};
